Abstract
Introduction: Management of pulmonary arterial hypertension (PAH) remains
challenging even in the contemporary era. Intravenous prostacyclin therapy, while
associated with decreased mortality, has practical limitations and requires significant
lifestyle modifications. The recently approved long-acting oral IP prostacyclin receptor
agonist for treatment of PAH, selexipag, is a non-prostanoid agent that vasodilates,
impacts remodeling (anti-proliferative), reduces endothelial cell dysfunction, inhibits
platelet aggregation (anti-thrombotic), and increases right heart inotropy.
Areas covered: This review discusses the limitations of non-oral prostacyclin therapy for
PAH and describes the factors which led to successful development of selexipag in in
vitro and preclinical studies. We review the pharmacokinetics and pharmacodynamics of
selexipag. We further discuss the methodology and results of phase II and III trials, which
led to approval of selexipag for PAH management.
Expert Opinion: As compared to previously developed oral prostacyclins, selexipag has
limited adverse effects despite similar or better efficacy. Its final place in the treatment
paradigm is not yet clear but it does represent a significant advance in the area of oral
PAH therapy.
Keywords: Pulmonary arterial hypertension, selexipag, prostacyclin

1. Introduction
Pulmonary hypertension (PH) is defined by the presence of a mean pulmonary arterial
pressures (mPAP) of more than 25mmHg at rest. Based on the etiopathogenesis, PH was
classified by the World Pulmonary Hypertension Society (WPHS) into five groups.
Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension (PAH) is WHO group 1 PH which is characterized by
the presence of pre-capillary changes in pulmonary vasculature. It is defined by the
presence of a mPAP greater than 25mmHg, a pulmonary artery occlusion pressure
(PAOP) less than or equal to 15mmHg and a pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) of
more than 3 Wood Units (240 dyne-s/cm5)[1].
1.1. Overview of the market
The last two decades have witnessed greater insights into the complex pathophysiological
pathways involved in PAH. Broadly, a variety of molecular pathways lead to five major
components which together constitute the PAH phenotype. These consist of
vasoconstriction, cellular proliferation (vascular smooth muscle and endothelial),
thrombosis, inflammation and metabolic changes. (Figure 1) These molecular pathways
interact at multiple levels and are not mutually exclusive [2].
These insights led to the development of experimental agents affecting these pathways.
However, multiple agents, which seemed effective in the preclinical studies, either were
ineffective in clinical trials or had unacceptable toxicity profiles. Some of the agents
which failed in clinical trials include imatinib (a tyrosine kinase inhibitor), a synthetic
formulation of vasoactive intestinal peptide (Aviptadil), fasudil (a Rho-kinase inhibitor),
various forms of inhaled nitric oxide, cicletanine (an endothelial nitric oxide synthase
coupler), simvastatin, and aspirin [3].
Overall, agents targeting non-vasoactive components of PAH have not yet been
successful in clinical investigations. Thus, currently approved therapies target the
vasoactive pathways. These include synthetic prostanoids, endothelin-1 receptor
antagonists (ERAs), phosphodiesterase-5 inhibitors (PDE5Is), and soluble guanylyl
cyclase agonists. Epoprostenol is the only agent shown to improve survival in a 12-week
trial in treatment-nave patients in the 1990s [4]. Due to significant improvement in
overall quality of medical management, some investigators argue that comparing
untreated PAH patients from the 1980s to placebo-treated patients in 2000s might not be
methodologically accurate. However, in the current era, we are unlikely to ever see a trial
randomizing patients to placebo alone.
Randomized Controlled Trials (RCTs) for PAH have traditionally considered Health-
Related Quality of Life (HR-QoL) a secondary end-point. Although the majority of
studies have reported improvement in some aspects of HR-QoL with use of all PAH
therapies [4-7], improvement with non-oral therapies has not been seen consistently [8]
and most improvement is seen with intravenous epoprostenol therapy. Thermostable
formulations for intravenous epoprostenol therapies have been developed, but there are
still significant practical challenges for its use (difficulty of use, line associated blood
stream infections, short half-life, concern for tachyphylaxis etc.) [9]. Since therapies
targeting the prostacyclin pathway are the cornerstone for PAH management, various
oral, subcutaneous and inhaled formulations have become available to overcome the
challenges of intravenous therapy. Subcutaneous and inhaled formulations still require
frequent administration and are associated with similar adverse effects as intravenous
therapy. Hence, there is a need to develop oral therapies the targeting prostacyclin
pathway.
Beraprost, a chemically stable oral prostacyclin analogue, was the first agent to be
investigated. An initial randomized double blind control study (ALPHABET) by Galie et
al showed significant improvement in 6-Minute Walk Distance and Borg Dyspnea Scale
at 12 weeks [10]. However, despite these initial results, beraprost failed to show a durable
response in the 6-Minute Walk Distance beyond 6 months of treatment in a longer
follow-up trial [11]. Thus, it was not approved by the Food and Drug Administration
(FDA). Of interest, despite a relatively non-selective mechanism of action, only 2
patients (3%) prematurely discontinued beraprost due to adverse effects [11].
Oral treprostinil (taken twice a day) was the next oral prostanoid to be investigated. The
FREEDOM-C trial [12], a multicenter double blind randomized controlled trial, enrolled
350 PAH patients on stable doses of an ERA, a PDE-5I, or both. In an intention-to-treat
analysis, there was a trend towards modest improvement in 6-Minute Walk Distance (11
meters, p= 0.07) with 16 weeks of therapy. However, there was 22% discontinuation rate
compared to 14% with placebo. The majority of participants discontinued therapy due to
adverse effects. In patients who were able to tolerate and continue the therapy, there was
a dose-dependent increase in the 6-Minute Walk Distance (4m with 1mg, 18m with 3.25
mg, 34m with 16mg). In an exploratory analysis, it appeared that the side effects (and
lack of efficacy) were due to the initial dose and the rapid titration scheme in the study.
After evaluating these results, the FDA denied approval of oral treprostinil. Thus, the
FREEDOM-C2 trial was undertaken with the hopes of minimizing adverse effects from
treprostinil with lower starting doses (0.25mg, 0.5mg and 1 mg) [13]. Published a year
later, the results were very similar to the FREEDOM-C trial; no significant improvement
in 6-Minute Walk Distance (10m, p=0.08). However, the discontinuation rate was lower
compared to the previous trial (16% with therapy compared to 10% with placebo). Based
on these results, the FDA again denied approval of treprostinil. FREEDOM-M trial [14],
a randomized trial evaluating the efficacy of treprostinil monotherapy, did show an
improvement in 6-Minute Walk Distance of 23 meters in a modified intention-to-treat
analysis (p<0.05). However, the discontinuation rate was high (22% for treprostinil vs
15.5% for placebo) and secondary endpoints were, in general, not positive. Since the
improvement in 6-Minute Walk Distance did not reach statistical significance in the
combination therapy trials (FREEDOM-C and C2 trials), the FREEDOM-EV trial
(NCT01560624, clinicaltrials.gov) was designed to look at co-primary end points (6-
Minute Walk Distance and time to clinical worsening) and is ongoing (results expected in
2017/2018). However, based on the FREEDOM-M data, the FDA approved oral
treprostinil as monotherapy for the treatment of PAH.
1.2. Introduction to the compound
Selexipag, an oral IP prostacyclin receptor agonist was recently approved by the FDA
based on results from a large phase 3 clinical trial (GRIPHON) [15]. Below, we describe
the pharmacodynamics, pharmacokinetics and clinical data of selexipag. We conclude
with our expert opinion regarding the past, present and the future of oral therapies
targeting the prostacyclin pathways.
2. Chemistry
The origin of selexipag dates back to the initial observation by Asaki et al in 2007 [16]
demonstrating that it was possible to achieve agonist activity at the prostacyclin receptor
with compounds lacking the prototypical prostanoid structure. Compound 1 (BMY-
42393), the initial agent with partial agonist activity, was tailored through a series of
modifications in order to achieve maximum receptor affinity (compound 12b) and most
stability (compound 26a) [17]. Compound 26a (later called selexipag, ACT-293987) has
an N-acylsulfonamide moiety (Figure 2) which is hydrolysed to carboxylic acid in vivo
(compound 12b, ACT-333679); this agent has a much higher potency than the parent
compound.
3. Therapeutic target and mechanism of action
When studied in pulmonary arterial smooth muscle cells, ACT-333679 leads to sustained
increase in intracellular cAMP, sustained cell relaxation and decrease in proliferation
[18]. Kuwano et al. tested the efficacy of these agents in inhibiting platelet aggregation in
human platelet-rich plasma; ACT-333679 was 26-fold more potent (IC50= 0.21uM)
platelet aggregation inhibitor than selexipag (IC50= 5.5uM) [19].
Kuwano, et al. studied the effects of selexipag and its active metabolite in the MCT-
induced PH rat model. It was associated with improvement in pulmonary arterial wall
hypertrophy (32.2% percentage wall thickness in untreated group vs 23.5% in selexipag
group) and endothelial function (relaxant response to papaverine and acetylcholine).
Similarly, there was significant improvement in the right ventricular systolic pressure (68
mmHg in the untreated group vs 51 mmHg in selexipag group) and compensatory right
ventricular hypertrophy [20].
4. Pharmacodynamics
There are a least seven types of human prostanoid receptors. These include DP receptors
(Prostaglandin D receptor), EP receptors 1-4 (Prostaglandin E receptors), FP receptor
(Prostaglandin F receptor) and IP receptor (Prostaglandin I receptor). Broadly they can be
classified into contractile receptors (EP1, EP3, FP) and dilatory receptors (IP, EP2, EP4,
DP) [21]. Whereas most beneficial effects in human PAH are thought to be derived from
activation of IP receptors, currently available prostanoid therapies have a variable degree
of affinity and potency for other receptors. Activation of non-IP receptors (such as the
EP3 receptor) can not only lead to a decrease in vasodilation derived via activation of IP
receptor, but also to adverse effects due to non-vascular distribution of these receptors
(such as gastrointestinal side effects). Kuwano, et al. determined that the IP receptor
binding affinity of ACT-333679 (Ki 20nM) is similar to treprostinil (Ki 32nM) and less
than iloprost (Ki 3.9nM) [20]. IP receptor binding affinity of selexipag (prodrug) was
found to be 13 times less than ACT-333679 (Ki 260nM). Receptor binding affinity (Ki)
at EP3 receptor for selexipag, ACT-333679 and beraprost is >10000nM, >10000nM and
0.68 nM, respectively. Decreased selectivity for non-IP receptors might explain the better
tolerability of selexipag than beraprost and other prostanoid therapies. Morrison et al
showed that oral administration of selexipag does not alter stomach emptying and
intestinal transport in rats, whereas beraprost leads to slowing of gastric transit [22]. In
this ex-vivo model, they showed that all prostanoids led to increase in contractility in the
gastric fundus, primarily mediated by EP3 and EP1 receptors. On the contrary, selexipag
or its active metabolite (ACT-333679) did not change gastric contractility.
In-vitro experiments have shown that with repeated or prolonged exposure to prostanoids,
IP receptors are desensitized through internalization and uncoupling of receptors. These
effects are mediated by the recruitment of beta-arrestin. Gatfield et al showed that ACT-
333679, when applied to recombinant Chinese Hamster Ovary cells expressing IP
receptors, led to significantly lesser recruitment of beta-arrestin than beraprost,
treprostinil or iloprost. This led to decreased internalization of IP receptors, and therefore,
efficacy in inducing cAMP response was retained [23]. The same group showed that
selexipag, when administered to spontaneously hypertensive rats, led to persistently
decreased mean arterial pressure (MAP) with return in MAP to baseline levels only with
discontinuation of the drug. Indeed, selectivity for the pulmonary circulation over the
systemic circulation is important for safe treatment of PAH. Importantly, in a phase III
clinical trial, patients treated with selexipag did not have significantly higher rates of
hypotension than the placebo group, suggesting selectivity for the pulmonary circulation,
and an acceptable safety profile [15]. On the contrary, intravenous administration of
treprostinil led to transient reduction of MAP followed by return to the baseline levels
within 36 hours, despite continuation of the drug [24].
5. Pharmacokinetics and metabolism
Selexipag is orally absorbed and exhibits dose-proportional PK measures up to single
doses of 800 mcg and multiple doses of 1800 mcg; however, its active metabolite (ACT-
333679) is slightly less than dose-proportional, such that for every 2-fold increase in
dose, there is approximately an 85% increase in exposure. There is no accumulation of
plasma concentration with twice daily dosing, and steady state levels of selexipag and
ACT-333679 are achieved within three days after oral administration, with plasma
exposure of ACT-333679 being 3- to 4-fold higher than to selexipag in healthy
volunteers [25]. The starting dose is 200 mcg twice daily, with increases of 200 mcg
twice daily every week up to the highest tolerated dose or 1600 mcg twice daily [26].
In a phase I, double-blind, placebo-controlled study, pharmacokinetics were determined
in 64 healthy male volunteers; for selexipag, the median time-to-peak concentration
(Tmax) was 1 hour with maximal plasma concentration (Cmax) of 1.98-7.98 ng/mL
following administration of 200 mcg of selexipag; for ACT-333679, the median Tmax was
3-4 hours with Cmax of 2.78-5.36 ng/mL following administration of 200 mcg of
selexipag. In a food-effect, open-label, randomized, two-period crossover study, 12 total
subjects were given a single dose of 400 mcg of selexipag following a 12-hour fast or
after a high-fat breakfast, and subjects were then crossed over to the other group during
the second study period. After a high-fat breakfast, oral absorption of selexipag was
delayed and the plasma exposure (AUC0-) to ACT-333679 was decreased by 27%; the
fed-group had significantly fewer adverse events, and thus, selexipag is administered
with food [27]. The oral bioavailability and volume of distribution of selexipag are not
known, but in vitro studies suggest selexipag and its metabolites are highly protein-bound
(~99%) [26].
Because patients with severe PAH may develop right-sided heart failure and subsequent
passive hepatic congestion, the effect of hepatic function on oral selexipag is important.
Selexipag is hydrolyzed by hepatic microsomal carboxylesterase 1 (CES-1) to its active
metabolite ACT-333679, and also metabolized by cytochrome P450 (CYP) 3A4 and
CYP2C8 to hydroxylated and alkylated end-products; ACT-333679 undergoes
glucuronidation by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase (UGT) 1A3 and UGT2B7, and both
selexipag and ACT-333679 are excreted in the bile. Selexipag has a mean terminal
elimination half-life (t1/2) of 0.8 to 2.5 hours and average apparent oral clearance of
35L/h; ACT-333679 has a t1/2 of 6 to 13 hours. The in vivo stability of selexipag is
conferred by its non-prostanoid ring structure, and slow conversion to ACT-333679. In a
4-group phase I study comparing subjects with mild hepatic impairment (n=8), moderate
hepatic impairment (n=8), severe hepatic impairment (n=2), and healthy subjects (n=8),
there was no significant difference in ACT-333679 levels in patients with mild hepatic
impairment (Child-Pugh class A), and therefore, no need for dose adjustment. However,
there was a two-fold increase in ACT-333679 levels in patients with moderate hepatic
impairment (Child-Pugh class B); thus, in these patients, the FDA recommends once
daily dosing starting at 200 mcg daily, and increasing the dose by 200 mcg daily every
week up to the highest tolerated dose or 1600 mcg once daily [28]. Because there were so
few patients in the severe hepatic impairment group, avoiding selexipag in these patients
is recommended [26].
In contrast, renal impairment does not appear to have significant pharmacokinetic effects
on selexipag. Although subjects with eGFR 15-29 mL/min/1.73 m2 exhibited a 40-70%
increase in ACT-333679 exposure, t1/2 was unchanged, suggesting that elimination was
not affected by renal function; therefore, since selexipag is titrated to tolerability, no dose
adjustment is necessary for renal impairment [29]. Similarly, body weight is inversely
correlated to plasma exposure, but t1/2 was unchanged, so no dose adjustment is
necessary. No dose adjustments are needed for age, gender, or ethnicity [26].

6. Clinical efficacy
The efficacy of selexipag for treating PAH was demonstrated in a phase II proof-of-
concept study, in which 43 adult patients with symptomatic PAH, on stable background
therapy with an ERA or a PDE-5 inhibitor, were randomized three to one to receive
selexipag or placebo; mean pulmonary vascular resistance decreased by 30% at 17 weeks
in the selexipag group compared with the placebo group. Secondary endpoints of
improvement in 6-minute walk distance (6MWD) (+24.7 m in selexipag group versus
+0.4 m in placebo group) or NT-pro-BNP (mean treatment effect -212.8 pgmL-1) were
not statistically significant, but the drug was well tolerated [32]; these findings were the
impetus for the larger, pivotal, phase III trial.
The results of the phase III, event-driven, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled
Prostacyclin Receptor Agonist in Pulmonary Arterial Hypertension (GRIPHON) trial led
to rapid FDA approval of selexipag for the treatment of PAH [15]. In this trial, 1156
patients with PAH, who were either receiving no therapy or stable background therapy
with an ERA or PDE-5 inhibitor, or both drugs were randomized to selexipag or placebo.
Enrollment required right heart catheterization to confirm the diagnosis of PAH, a
minimum PVR of 5 Wood units and 6MWD of 40-450 m; patients on prostacyclin
analogue therapy were excluded. Patients then underwent a 12-week dose titration phase
in which selexipag was started at 200 mcg twice daily and titrated on a weekly basis in
twice-daily increments of 200 mcg to the maximum tolerated dose or 1600 mcg twice
daily, at which time, they entered the maintenance phase of the study. While dosages
could be decreased at any time during the study, during the maintenance phase dosages
could not be increased until week 26.
The primary event-driven endpoint was a composite of death or complication related to
PAH, including hospitalization for worsening PAH, disease progression (defined as a
decrease from baseline of at least 15% in 6MWD accompanied by worsening in WHO
functional class or need for additional treatment for PAH), death from any cause,
initiation of parenteral prostanoid therapy or long-term oxygen therapy for worsening of
PAH, need for lung transplantation or balloon atrial septostomy for worsening PAH. The
risk of this primary composite endpoint was reduced in the selexipag group compared to
the placebo group by 40% (HR 0.60, 99% CI 0.46-0.78, p < 0.001). Overall, 397 patients
experienced a primary endpoint event, 41.6% in the placebo group and 27.0% in the
selexipag group (number-needed-to-treat of 7); 81.9% of these events were due to disease
progression and hospitalization. The efficacy was independent of background therapy as
the selexipag and placebo groups were matched in terms of number of patients who were
treatment-nave or receiving ERA and/or PDE-5I. (20.4% no therapy, 14.7% ERA,
32.4% PDE-5I, 32.5% ERA + PDE-5I). Analyzing the secondary endpoint, 6MWD,
required imputing missing data points for 21.6% of the patients; thus, although there was
a statistically significant increase in 6MWD at 26 weeks, these data should be interpreted
with caution until more robust clinical data are available. Similarly, NT-proBNP and
death due to worsening PAH were lower in the selexipag group, but again, these results
were tested on observed data via a hierarchical, and therefore, exploratory manner; direct
conclusions should not be drawn from these secondary analyses. There are several
ongoing clinical trials of selexipag (Table 2).
7. Safety, tolerability, toxicity, and potential off-target effects
Tolerability has limited the use of oral prostanoids, such as oral treprostinil (especially if
dosed twice daily instead of three times daily) but, selexipag is generally well tolerated
and only a minority of patients discontinue the drug due to adverse events. In a phase I,
double-blind, placebo-controlled, tolerability study, 64 healthy male volunteers were
given selexipag at increasing doses; adverse events occurred with increasing frequency
and intensity at doses higher than 400 mcg [27]. In the phase III GRIPHON trial, the
study drug discontinuation rate was twice as high in the selexipag compared to placebo
group (14% vs 7% over a three year period) but substantially lower than the
discontinuation rate of oral treprostinil (22% in a twelve week period) [12]; the most
common adverse events were headache (65.2%), diarrhea (42.4%), nausea (33.6%), jaw
pain (25.7%), worsening of PAH (21.9%), vomiting (18.1%), extremity pain (16.9%),
dyspnea (16.0%), myalgia (16.0%) [15]. Adverse effects were generally mild or
moderate, which accounts for the low discontinuation rate.
8. Drug-drug interactions
Selexipag and its active metabolite do not activate or inhibit the P450 enzyme system, but
concomitant use of CYP2C8 inhibitors (e.g. gemfibrozil) with selexipag should be
avoided as this could lead to high levels of selexipag [26]. There are few described
significant interactions with other drugs, and selexipag does not have significant
interactions with lopinavir/ritonavir [30], warfarin [31], ERA, PDE-5I, or a combination
of ERA+PDE-5I [26].
9. Regulatory affairs
The oral IP receptor agonist, selexipag, is easy to dose, well-tolerated, and improved the
event rate of a composite outcome including death or complication related to PAH. Thus,
selexipag was promptly granted FDA and European Medicines Agency (EMA) approval
for this fatal disease with limited therapeutic options.
10. Conclusion
Intravenous prostacyclin therapy, the only PAH therapy shown to prolong survival, has
multiple limitations and there is dire need for development of oral therapies targeting this
pathway. Whereas bearprost did not lead to persistent improvement in 6MWD, oral
treprostinil had significant adverse effects. Selexipag, a long acting non-prostanoid oral
IP receptor agonist, offers limited adverse effects despite similar or better efficacy
compared to these agents, even when added to double background therapy, and was
recently approved by the FDA and EMA. Multiple ongoing trials are currently evaluating
the role of selexipag in PAH therapy.
11. Expert Opinion
The search for an effective oral prostacyclin therapy for PAH has long been sought. The
first oral prostacyclin, beraprost, although effective short-term, did not exhibit a durable
response (6MWD returned to baseline at 1 year); therefore, it was not approved by the
FDA.
Oral treprostinil was eventually approved by the FDA, after two failed attempts, for
treatment of PAH as monotherapy, although it is highly unlikely that it would ever be
used in this fashion because of the difficulty in titration and the ease of other oral agents.
Despite the lack of efficacy in two FREEDOM-C trials, it is more likely to be used as
additional therapy in patients on a background ERA or PDE-5I or both and, possibly, in
very selected patients who might be transitioned from systemic treprostinil. Additionally,
all the FREEDOM trials used twice daily dosing, leading to intolerable side effects in a
large number of patients and, thereby, limiting efficacy. It is now clear that thrice daily
dosing allows for improved tolerability and higher doses (and, presumably, greater
efficacy). The currently enrolling FREEDOM-EV trial is using this thrice daily dosing
scheme - it will be interesting to see if this dosing protocol leads to more robust results
than previous clinical trials. Lastly, as with selexipag (see below), oral treprostinil has not
been evaluated in FC IIIb/IV PAH patients and should not be considered a substitute for
systemic therapy in these advanced patients.
Selexipag was recently approved as the first agent in its class (a non-prostanoid IP
prostacyclin receptor agonist) based on the results of the GRIPHON trial demonstrating a
40% reduction in death or complication related to PAH in those patients receiving
selexipag. Thus, currently available data suggest that selexipag is better tolerated and/or
more effective than beraprost or oral treprostinil. The question now is: how to use
selexipag and for whom should it be considered.
Based on the study protocol, it is important to titrate the drug to the maximum tolerated
dose (up to a maximal dose of 1600mcg twice daily). Even though the risk reduction in
GRIPHON was similar regardless of the dose achieved, one should not infer that all
doses are necessarily equal unless they are increased to the highest tolerable dose. The
variation in dose achieved may be due to differences in receptors (i.e. receptor density,
receptor kinetics) among individuals. The salient points are: 1) uptitrate selexipag to the
highest tolerated dose; and 2) follow the current dosing scheme - uptitration weekly as
tolerated. In GRIPHON, 14% of the patients who received selexipag discontinued drug
due to side effects; the side effects observed either during uptitration or maintenance are
similar to those of prostanoids and should be managed accordingly. Hopefully, with
greater experience, the side effects and the number of discontinuations can be decreased
as providers become more familiar with usage of the drug.
Who should be considered for treatment with selexipag? In GRIPHON, selexipag was
equally effective whether the patient was treatment naive, was receiving background
therapy with an ERA or a PDE-5I, or was receiving background therapy with both. Thus,
from these data, one could argue that almost everyone is a candidate. That may be an
overstatement, but with the current trend of "more is better" in PAH treatment, based on
data from the recently completed large trials (PATENT, SERAPHIN, GRIPHON, and
AMBITION), it is now the paradigm to consider combination therapy in almost all
patients, be he/she treatment naive or treatment experienced. Certainly, selexipag should
be considered in patients on background therapy who have not achieved an expected
level of clinical, imaging and/or hemodynamic improvement and are not yet in need of a
systemic prostanoid. Should it be considered in patients who are doing "well" on current
treatment? This is not quite as clear because that information (differentiation between
patients doing well and those not) was not available in GRIPHON. This will likely
become more apparent in further evaluation of the drug and/or its use is more
widespread.
Selexipag should not be equated to nor considered a substitute for systemic prostanoids.
GRIPHON included very few FC IIIb/IV PAH patients; thus there is really no experience
with the drug in these patients. Moreover, even if it were to be effective in patients who
are this advanced, the titration scheme currently employed would make it difficult to
reach the presumed effective dose rapidly. In sum, patients who need systemic
prostanoids by functional and/or hemodynamic criteria still need them and should not be
jeopardized by use of this oral agent. But, could early use of selexipag, in combination,
with other oral agents, decrease progression of disease sufficiently to avoid the need for
systemic prostanoids? Although that question has not been specifically investigated, one
hopes that earlier use of a prostanoid agent might, at least in some patients, accomplish
this.
Could selected patients who are stable and improved on other prostanoids be transitioned
safely to selexipag? This is currently unknown - there are really very limited data
available that address this issue. This has not prevented nor will it prevent some
practitioners from attempting such a transition. However, there is no information on the
equivalency of the dose of selexipag to the dose of other prostanoids. And, if this
transition fails, there are no data demonstrating that putting the patient back on the
original prostanoid will be successful. Obviously this issue is extremely important and
does need further evaluation. The first investigation addressing this issue is now fully
enrolled; TRANSIT-1 is evaluating transition from inhaled treprostinil to selexipag. This,
and other future studies, will address this issue in detail. For now, when thinking of such
transitions, patient safety should be the utmost consideration.
To summarize, selexipag is an exciting addition to the treatment choices for patients with
PAH. Its final place in the treatment paradigm is not yet perfectly clear but it does
represent a significant advance in the area of oral PAH therapy.
